<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9869466622835></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9869466622835><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=9869466622835>RE: Groups!?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=9869466622835#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Apr 10th 7:51 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>You're on the right track! Don't worry too much about those large-scale wipeouts. They do happen from time to time, despite your best planning. You will learn to avoid more of them as you gain experience with different zones and creatures...what their habits are, what paths they like to take to get from point A to B, etc.<br><br>You've learned the basic /assist rules, which is a great lesson to learn at your level. A lot of players don't catch on for a LONG time. However, following this rule ALL the time will definitely help you later down the road as you start playing in trickier zones.<br><br>Here's what I've found works good for a magician in a group:<br><br>*) Make sure your group is well supplied. Summon up some bandages so everyone can practice their Bind Wound skill, and to help stretch out your cleric's mana. If you can summon a weapon that is better than one of your groupmates, then give them the better weapon! You can also summon up food, water, and lightsources if you need to. It's not the most glamorous job, but it will save some time and money for your group.<br><br>*) If you have some good tanks in your group (warriors, rangers, rogues, monks), give your pet the "/pet no taunt" command as soon as you summon it up. This will keep your pet from getting into too much trouble by making the mobs too mad at him; it also helps the tanks better control the flow of the battle. Also, pick a nice spot in the back of your "kill zone" and give your pet the "/pet guard here" command. This way, your pet won't start wandering all over the zone and getting lots of orcs coming out of nowhere to beat on you.<br><br>*) You have a spell to heal your pet now! So tell the cleric not to worry about your pet's hitpoints, you will take care of that. She can save up her mana for healing the tanks.<br><br>*) Wait for your tanks to start beating on a mob. You and your pet should just stand in the back of the group for a few seconds while everyone else gets situated in battle. Have your main tank targetted, and put your Shield of Fire on him right as the battle gets started. It doesn't last very long yet, but it will get much better with time! And it's good to get in the practice of using your damage shield at the start of each battle.<br><br>*) /assist the main tank, make sure your target has changed to orc_centurion00 or whatever, and then give your pet the /pet attack command. Now your pet is contributing to the overall damage, so you can sit back for a few rounds and heal your pet when it gets low.<br><br>*) Use your big damage spells towards the end of the battle to quickly finish off a mob before it starts whimpering and running off. If you do too much spell damage at the beginning of the fight, that orc might decide to skip the warrior and come straight for you! So be conservative with your mana and use it when it's safer and more efficient to use. Also, if you are conservative with your mana, and then two more orcs decide to join the fight and you weren't expecting them, you've got enough mana to help cut through them and save they day for your group.<br><br>*) Don't feel like you aren't contributing to the group if you aren't casting damage spells all the time. Remember, your pet is contributing a lot of damage all by itself. You are supporting your pet by keeping it healed, and you are being thrifty with your mana so you can help burn through monsters when the situation starts looking rough.<br><br>Of course, you do have to amend these rules sometimes depending on the makeup of your group. You were in a group that didn't have a lot of tank support, and at your levels no classes really have good crowd control (but it won't be long before you'll really appreciate a good enchanter in your group).<br><br>The only rule that really counts, though, is that when everyone logs out for the night, they all agree that they had a lot of fun!<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
